<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	The Company&#146;s risk-management and compliance programs or functions may not be effective
	in mitigating risk and loss.
</B>
	The Company maintains an enterprise risk-management program that is designed to identify, quantify, monitor, report, and control the risks that it faces. These include interest-rate risk, credit risk, liquidity risk,
	market risk, operational risk, reputational risk, and compliance risk. The Company also maintains a compliance program to identify, measure, assess, and report on its adherence to applicable law, policies, and procedures. While the Company assesses
	and improves these programs on an ongoing basis, there can be no assurance that its frameworks or models for risk management, compliance, and related controls will effectively mitigate risk and limit losses in its business. If conditions or
	circumstances arise that expose flaws or gaps in the Company&#146;s risk-management or compliance programs or if its controls break down, the performance and value of the Company&#146;s business could be adversely affected. The Company could be
	negatively impacted as well if, despite adequate programs being in place, its risk-management or compliance personnel are ineffective in executing them and mitigating risk and loss.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Liquidity is essential to the Company and its business or performance could be adversely affected by constraints in, or increased costs
	for, funding.
</B>
	The Company defines liquidity as the ability to fund increases in assets and meet obligations as they come due, all without incurring unacceptable losses. Banks are especially vulnerable to liquidity risk because of their role in
	the maturity transformation of demand or short-term deposits into longer-term loans or other extensions of credit. The Company, like other financial-services companies, relies to a significant extent on external sources of funding (such as deposits
	and borrowings) for the liquidity needed to conduct its business. A number of factors beyond the Company&#146;s control, however, could have a detrimental impact on the availability or cost of that funding and thus on its liquidity. These include
	market disruptions, changes in its credit ratings or the sentiment of its investors, the state of the regulatory environment and monetary and fiscal policies, declines in the value of its investment securities, the loss of substantial deposit
	relationships, financial or systemic shocks, significant counterparty failures, and reputational damage. Unexpected declines or limits on the dividends declared and paid by the Company&#146;s subsidiaries also could adversely affect its liquidity
	position. While the Company&#146;s policies and controls are designed to ensure that it maintains adequate liquidity to conduct its business in the ordinary course even in a stressed environment, there can be no assurance that its liquidity position
	will never become compromised. In such an event, the Company may be required to sell assets at a loss in order to continue its operations. This could damage the performance and value of its business, prompt regulatory intervention, and harm its
	reputation, and if the condition were to persist for any appreciable period of time, its viability as a going concern could be threatened. See &#147;Quantitative and Qualitative Disclosures About Market Risk&#151;Liquidity Risk&#148; in Part II,
	Item 7A of this report beginning on page 57 for a discussion of how the Company monitors and manages liquidity risk.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	If the
	Company&#146;s subsidiaries are unable to make dividend payments or distributions to the Company, it may be unable to satisfy its obligations to counterparties or creditors or make dividend payments to its shareholders.
</B>
	The Company is a legal
	entity separate and distinct from its bank and nonbank subsidiaries and depends on dividend payments and distributions from those subsidiaries to fund its obligations to counterparties and creditors and its dividend payments to shareholders. See
	&#147;Regulation and Supervision&#151;Requirements Affecting the Relationships among the Company, Its Subsidiaries, and Other Affiliates&#148; in Part I, Item 1 of this report beginning on page&nbsp;6. Any of the Company&#146;s subsidiaries,
	however, may be unable to make dividend payments or distributions to the Company, including as a result of a deterioration in the subsidiary&#146;s performance, investments in the subsidiary&#146;s own future growth, or regulatory or supervisory
	requirements. If any subsidiary were unable to remain viable as a going concern, moreover, the Company&#146;s right to participate in a distribution of assets would be subject to the prior claims of the subsidiary&#146;s creditors (including, in the
	case of the Bank, its depositors and the FDIC).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	An inability to attract, retain, or motivate qualified employees could adversely
	affect the Company&#146;s business or performance.
</B>
	Skilled employees are the Company&#146;s most important resource, and competition for talented people is intense. Even though compensation is among the Company&#146;s highest expenses, it may
	not be able to locate and hire the best people, keep them with the Company, or properly motivate them to perform at a high level. Recent scrutiny of compensation practices, especially in the financial-services industry, has made this
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	17
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage18"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D317189D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	only more difficult. In addition, some parts of the Company&#146;s business are particularly dependent on key personnel, including investment management, asset servicing, and commercial lending.
	If the Company were to lose and find itself unable to replace these personnel or other skilled employees or if the competition for talent drove its compensation costs to unsustainable levels, the Company&#146;s business, results of operations, and
	financial condition could be negatively impacted.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	The Company is subject to a variety of litigation and other proceedings, which could
	adversely affect its business or performance.
</B>
	The Company is involved from time to time in a variety of judicial, alternative-dispute, and other proceedings arising out of its business or operations. The Company establishes reserves for claims
	when appropriate under generally accepted accounting principles, but costs often can be incurred in connection with a matter before any reserve has been created. The Company also maintains insurance policies to mitigate the cost of litigation and
	other proceedings, but these policies have deductibles, limits, and exclusions that may diminish their value or efficacy. Despite the Company&#146;s efforts to appropriately reserve for claims and insure its business and operations, the actual costs
	associated with resolving a claim may be substantially higher than amounts reserved or covered. Substantial legal claims, even if not meritorious, could have a detrimental impact on the Company&#146;s business, results of operations, and financial
	condition and could cause reputational harm.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Changes in accounting standards could impact the Company&#146;s financial statements and
	reported earnings.
</B>
	Accounting standard-setting bodies, such as the Financial Accounting Standards Board, periodically change the financial accounting and reporting standards that affect the preparation of the Company&#146;s Consolidated
	Financial Statements. These changes are beyond the Company&#146;s control and could have a meaningful impact on its Consolidated Financial Statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	The Company&#146;s selection of accounting methods, assumptions, and estimates could impact its financial statements and reported
	earnings.
</B>
	To comply with generally accepted accounting principles, management must sometimes exercise judgment in selecting, determining, and applying accounting methods, assumptions, and estimates. This can arise, for example, in the
	determination of the allowance for loan losses, the calculation of deferred tax assets, the evaluation of goodwill for potential impairments, or the determination of the fair value of assets or liabilities. Furthermore, accounting methods,
	assumptions and estimates are part of acquisition purchase accounting and the calculation of the fair value of assets and liabilities that have been purchased, including credit-impaired loans. The judgments required of management can involve
	difficult, subjective, or complex matters with a high degree of uncertainty, and several different judgments could be reasonable under the circumstances and yet result in significantly different results being reported. See &#147;Critical Accounting
	Policies and Estimates&#148; in Part II, Item 7 of this report beginning on page 48. If management&#146;s judgments are later determined to have been inaccurate, the Company may experience unexpected losses that could be substantial.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	The Company&#146;s ability to successfully make opportunistic acquisitions is subject to significant risks, including the risk that
	government authorities will not provide the requisite approvals, the risk that integrating acquisitions may be more difficult, costly, or time consuming than expected, and the risk that the value of acquisitions may be less than anticipated.
</B>
	The
	Company may make opportunistic acquisitions of other financial-services companies or businesses from time to time. These acquisitions may be subject to regulatory approval, and there can be no assurance that the Company will be able to obtain that
	approval in a timely manner or at all. Even when the Company is able to obtain regulatory approval, the failure of other closing conditions to be satisfied or waived could delay the completion of an acquisition for a significant period of time or
	prevent it from occurring altogether. Any failure or delay in closing an acquisition could adversely affect the Company&#146;s reputation, business, results of operations, financial condition, or prospects.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Additionally, acquisitions involve numerous risks and uncertainties, including lower-than-expected performance or higher-than-expected costs,
	difficulties related to integration, diversion of management&#146;s attention from other business activities, changes in relationships with customers or counterparties, and the potential loss of key employees. An acquisition also could be dilutive
	to the Company&#146;s current shareholders if its common stock were issued to fully or partially pay or fund the purchase price. The Company, moreover, may
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	18
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage19"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D317189D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	not be successful in identifying acquisition candidates, integrating acquired companies or businesses, or realizing the expected value from acquisitions. There is significant competition for
	valuable acquisition targets, and the Company may not be able to acquire other companies or businesses on attractive terms or at all. There can be no assurance that the Company will pursue future acquisitions, and the Company&#146;s ability to grow
	and successfully compete in its markets and regions may be impaired if it chooses not to pursue or is unable to successfully complete acquisitions.
</P>

<EFX_PROPERTIES>
<A NAME="FIS_PROPERTIES"></A>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR STYLE = "PAGE-BREAK-INSIDE:AVOID">
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
<A NAME="D317189D10K_HTM_TX317189_4">
</A>
	ITEM&nbsp;2.
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
</B>
<B>
<I>
	PROPERTIES
</I>
</B>
<B>
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company&#146;s headquarters building, the UMB Bank
	Building, is located at 1010 Grand Boulevard in downtown Kansas City, Missouri, and opened in July 1986. All 250,000 square feet is occupied by departments and customer service functions of the Bank, as well as offices of the Company.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Other main facilities of the Bank in downtown Kansas City, Missouri are located at 928 Grand Boulevard (185,000 square feet); 906 Grand
	Boulevard (140,000 square feet); and 1008 Oak Street (180,000 square feet). Both the 928 Grand and 906 Grand buildings house backroom support functions. The 928 Grand building also houses Scout. Additionally, within the 906 Grand building there is
	8,000 square feet of space leased to several small tenants. The 928 Grand building underwent a major renovation during 2004 and 2005. The 928 Grand building is connected to the UMB Bank Building (1010 Grand) by an enclosed elevated pedestrian
	walkway. The 1008 Oak building, which opened during the second quarter of 1999, houses the Company&#146;s operations and data processing functions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Bank leases 52,000 square feet in the Hertz Building located in the heart of the commercial sector of downtown St. Louis, Missouri. This
	location has a full-service banking center and is home to some operational and administrative support functions. The Bank also leases 30,000 square feet on the first, second, third, and fifth floors of the 1670 Broadway building located in the
	financial district of downtown Denver, Colorado. The location has a full-service banking center and is home to additional operational and administrative support functions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As of December&nbsp;31, 2016, the Bank operated a total of 106 banking centers and three wealth management offices.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	UMBFS leases 88,944 square feet at 235 West Galena Street in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, for its fund services operations headquarters.
	Additionally, UMBFS leases 37,300 square feet at 2225 Washington Boulevard in Ogden, Utah, and 6,302 square fee in 223 Wilmington West Chester Pike in Chadds Ford, Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Additional information with respect to properties, premises and equipment is presented in Note 1, &#147;Summary of Significant Accounting
	Policies,&#148; and Note 8, &#147;Premises and Equipment,&#148; in the Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements in Item 8, pages 67 and 89 of this report.
</P>
</EFX_PROPERTIES>

	On April&nbsp;26, 2016, the Company announced a plan to repurchase up to two million shares of common stock.
	This plan will terminate on April&nbsp;25, 2017. The Company has not made any repurchases other than through this plan. All open market share purchases under the share repurchase plans are intended to be within the scope of Rule
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	10b-18
</FONT>
	promulgated under the Exchange Act.

	ITEM&nbsp;7.

<B>
<I>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS OF FINANCIAL
	CONDITION AND RESULTS OF OPERATIONS
</I>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	This Management&#146;s Discussion and Analysis highlights the material changes in the results of operations and changes in financial condition
	for each of the three years in the period ended December&nbsp;31, 2016. It should be read in conjunction with the accompanying Consolidated Financial Statements, Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements, and other financial statistics appearing
	elsewhere in this Annual Report on Form
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	10-K.
</FONT>
	Results of operations for the periods included in this review are not necessarily indicative of results to be attained during any future period.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	CAUTIONARY NOTICE ABOUT FORWARD-LOOKING STATEMENTS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	From time to time the Company has made, and in the future will make, forward-looking statements within the meaning of the Private Securities
	Litigation Reform Act of 1995. These statements can be identified by the fact that they do not relate strictly to historical or current facts. Forward-looking statements often use words such as &#147;believe,&#148; &#147;expect,&#148;
	&#147;anticipate,&#148; &#147;intend,&#148; &#147;estimate,&#148; &#147;project,&#148; &#147;outlook,&#148; &#147;forecast,&#148; &#147;target,&#148; &#147;trend,&#148; &#147;plan,&#148; &#147;goal,&#148; or other words of comparable meaning or
	future-tense or conditional verbs such as &#147;may,&#148; &#147;will,&#148; &#147;should,&#148; &#147;would,&#148; or &#147;could.&#148; Forward-looking statements convey the Company&#146;s expectations, intentions, or forecasts about future
	events, circumstances, results, or aspirations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	This report, including any information incorporated by reference in this report, contains
	forward-looking statements. The Company also may make forward-looking statements in other documents that are filed or furnished with the SEC. In addition, the Company may make forward-looking statements orally or in writing to investors, analysts,
	members of the media, or others.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	All forward-looking statements, by their nature, are subject to assumptions, risks, and uncertainties,
	which may change over time and many of which are beyond the Company&#146;s control. You should not rely on any forward-looking statement as a prediction or guarantee about the future. Actual future objectives, strategies, plans, prospects,
	performance, conditions, or results may differ materially from those set forth in any forward-looking statement. While no list of assumptions, risks, or uncertainties could be complete, some of the factors that may cause actual results or other
	future events, circumstances, or aspirations to differ from those in forward-looking statements include:
</P>

<EFX_RESULTS_OF_OPERATIONS>
<A NAME="FIS_RESULTS_OF_OPERATIONS"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Results of Operations
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Overview
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company focuses on the
	following four core strategic objectives. Management believes these strategic objectives will guide its efforts to achieving its vision, to deliver
<I>
</I>
	the unparalleled customer experience, all the while seeking to improve net income and
	strengthen the balance sheet while undertaking prudent risk management.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	23
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage24"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D317189D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The first strategic objective is a focus to continuously improve operating efficiencies. The
	Company has recently focused on identifying efficiencies that simplify our organizational and reporting structures, streamline back office functions and take advantage of synergies and newer technologies among various platforms and distribution
	networks. During 2015, the Company identified a total of $32.9&nbsp;million in annualized savings related to the elimination of employee positions and business process improvements. At December&nbsp;31, 2016, all but $3&nbsp;million of these savings
	had been recognized, which decelerated the growth rate of the Company&#146;s operating expenses. The remainder of such savings is expected to be phased in throughout 2017. In addition, the Company has and expects to continue identifying ongoing
	efficiencies through the normal course of business that, when combined with increased revenue, will contribute to improved operating leverage. During 2016, total revenue increased 10.6&nbsp;percent, while noninterest expense increased
	4.0&nbsp;percent. As part of this initiative, the Company continues to invest in technological advances that it believes will help management drive operating leverage in the future through improved data analysis and automation. The Company also
	continues to evaluate core systems and will invest in enhancements that it believes will yield operating efficiencies.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The second
	strategic objective is a focus on net interest income through profitable loan and deposit growth and the optimization of the balance sheet. During 2016, we made progress on this strategy, as illustrated by an increase in net interest income of
	$83.3&nbsp;million, or 20.2&nbsp;percent, from the previous year. The Company has continued to show increased net interest income in a historically low interest rate environment through the effects of increased volume and mix of average earning
	assets and a low cost of funds in its Consolidated Balance Sheets. In addition, on May&nbsp;31, 2015 (the Acquisition Date), the Company acquired all of the outstanding common stock of Marquette Financial Companies (Marquette). Information related
	to the acquisition is set forth in Note 15, &#147;Acquisitions,&#148; in the Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements, which can be found in Part II, Item 8, pages 101 through 103 of this report. The Marquette acquisition added earning assets
	with an acquired value of $1.2&nbsp;billion to the Company&#146;s Consolidated Balance Sheets. Average earning assets at December&nbsp;31, 2016, increased $1.8&nbsp;billion, or 10.7&nbsp;percent from December&nbsp;31, 2015. The funding for these
	assets was driven primarily by a 17.6&nbsp;percent increase in average interest-bearing liabilities. Average loan balances increased $1.6&nbsp;billion, or 18.6&nbsp;percent compared to the same period in 2015. Net interest margin, on a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	tax-equivalent
</FONT>
	basis, increased 24 basis points compared to the same period in 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The third
	strategic objective is to grow the Company&#146;s revenue from noninterest sources. The Company has continued to emphasize its diverse operations throughout all economic cycles. This strategy has provided revenue diversity, helping to reduce the
	impact of sustained low interest rates and position the Company to benefit in periods of growth. During 2016, noninterest income increased $9.6&nbsp;million, or 2.1&nbsp;percent, to $476.1&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016,
	compared to the same period in 2015. This change is discussed in greater detail below under Noninterest income. The Company continues to emphasize its asset management, brokerage, bankcard services, healthcare services, institutional banking, and
	treasury management businesses. At December&nbsp;31, 2016, noninterest income represented 49.0&nbsp;percent of total revenues, compared to 53.1&nbsp;percent at December&nbsp;31, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The fourth strategic objective is a focus on capital management. The Company places a significant emphasis on maintaining a strong capital
	position, which management believes promotes investor confidence, provides access to funding sources under favorable terms, and enhances the Company&#146;s ability to capitalize on organic growth, new business development, and acquisition
	opportunities. The Company continues to maximize shareholder value through a mix of reinvesting in organic growth, evaluating acquisition opportunities that complement the strategies, increasing dividends over time, and appropriately utilizing a
	share repurchase program. At December&nbsp;31, 2016, the Company had a total risk-based capital ratio of 12.87&nbsp;percent and $2.0&nbsp;billion in total shareholders&#146; equity, an increase of $68.7&nbsp;million, or 3.6&nbsp;percent, compared to
	total shareholders&#146; equity at December&nbsp;31, 2015. The Company repurchased 323,058 shares of common stock at an average price of $50.66 per share during 2016 and paid $49.0&nbsp;million in dividends, which represents a 6.6&nbsp;percent
	increase compared to dividends paid during 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	24
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage25"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D317189D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Earnings Summary
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company recorded consolidated net income of $158.8&nbsp;million for the year-ended December&nbsp;31, 2016. This represents a
	36.8&nbsp;percent increase over 2015. Net income for 2015 was $116.1&nbsp;million, or a decrease of 3.8&nbsp;percent compared to 2014. Basic earnings per share for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, were $3.25 per share compared to $2.46 per
	share in 2015, an increase of 32.1&nbsp;percent. Basic earnings per share were $2.69 per share in 2014, or a decrease of 8.6&nbsp;percent from 2014 to 2015. Fully diluted earnings per share increased 32.0&nbsp;percent from 2015 to 2016, and
	decreased 7.9&nbsp;percent from 2014 to 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company&#146;s net interest income increased to $495.3&nbsp;million in 2016 compared to
	$412.1&nbsp;million in 2015 and $350.1&nbsp;million in 2014. In total, a favorable volume variance coupled with a favorable rate variance, resulted in an $83.3&nbsp;million increase in net interest income in 2016, compared to 2015. See Table 2 on
	page 28. The favorable volume variance on earning assets was predominantly driven by the increase in average loan balances of $1.6&nbsp;billion, or 18.6&nbsp;percent, for 2016 compared to the same period in 2015. Net interest margin, on a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	tax-equivalent
</FONT>
	basis, increased to 2.88&nbsp;percent for 2016, compared to 2.64&nbsp;percent for the same period in 2015. The Marquette acquisition added earning assets with an acquired value of $1.2&nbsp;billion
	primarily from loan balances with an acquired value of $980.4&nbsp;million at May&nbsp;31, 2015. Marquette also added interest-bearing liabilities with an acquired value of $910.8&nbsp;million primarily from interest-bearing deposits of
	$708.7&nbsp;million at May&nbsp;31, 2015. Despite the current low interest rate environment, the Company continues to see benefit from interest-free funds. The impact of this benefit increased one basis point compared to 2015 and is illustrated on
	Table 3 on page 29. The current economic environment has made it difficult to anticipate the future of the Company&#146;s margins. The magnitude and duration of this impact will be largely dependent upon the FRB&#146;s policy decisions and market
	movements. See Table 19 in Item 7A on page 52 for an illustration of the impact of an interest rate increase or decrease on net interest income as of December&nbsp;31, 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company had an increase of $9.6&nbsp;million, or 2.1&nbsp;percent, in noninterest income in 2016, as compared to 2015, and a
	$32.2&nbsp;million, or 6.5&nbsp;percent, decrease in 2015, compared to 2014. The increase in 2016 is primarily attributable to unrealized equity gains on alternative investments, increase in bank-owned and company-owned life insurance income, and
	brokerage income, partially offset by lower trust and securities processing income. The change in noninterest income in 2016 from 2015, and 2015 from 2014 is illustrated on Table 6 on page 32.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Noninterest expense increased in 2016 by $28.2&nbsp;million, or 4.0&nbsp;percent, compared to 2015 and increased by $38.1&nbsp;million, or
	5.7&nbsp;percent, in 2015 compared to 2014. The increase in 2016 is primarily driven by an increase of $26.3&nbsp;million, or 6.5&nbsp;percent, in salary and employee benefit expense. The increase in noninterest expense in 2016 from 2015, and 2015
	from 2014 is illustrated on Table 7 on page 33.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Net Interest Income
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Net interest income is a significant source of the Company&#146;s earnings and represents the amount by which interest income on earning assets
	exceeds the interest expense paid on liabilities. The volume of interest earning assets and the related funding sources, the overall mix of these assets and liabilities, and the interest rates paid on each affect net interest income. Table 2
	summarizes the change in net interest income resulting from changes in volume and rates for 2016, 2015 and 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Net interest margin,
	presented in Table 1 on page 26, is calculated as net interest income on a fully tax equivalent basis (FTE) as a percentage of average earning assets. Net interest income is presented on a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	tax-equivalent
</FONT>
	basis
	to adjust for the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	tax-exempt
</FONT>
	status of earnings from certain loans and investments, which are primarily obligations of state and local governments. A critical component of net interest income and related net
	interest margin is the percentage of earning assets funded by interest-free sources. Table 3 analyzes net interest margin for the three years ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015 and 2014. Net interest income, average balance sheet amounts and the
	corresponding yields earned and rates paid for the years 2014 through 2016 are presented in Table 1 below.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	25
</P>

<A NAME="eolPage27"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D317189D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR STYLE = "PAGE-BREAK-INSIDE:AVOID">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(1)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Interest income and yields are stated on a fully
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	tax-equivalent
</FONT>
	(FTE) basis, using a marginal tax rate of 35%. The
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	tax-equivalent
</FONT>
	interest
	income and yields give effect to
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	tax-exempt
</FONT>
	interest income net of the disallowance of interest expense, for federal income tax purposes related to certain
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	tax-free
</FONT>
	assets. Rates earned/paid may not compute to the rates shown due to presentation in millions. The
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	tax-equivalent
</FONT>
	interest income totaled $31.0&nbsp;million, $23.8&nbsp;million, and $21.2&nbsp;million in 2016,
	2015, and 2014, respectively.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR STYLE = "PAGE-BREAK-INSIDE:AVOID">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(2)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Loan fees are included in interest income. Such fees totaled $13.3&nbsp;million, $11.4&nbsp;million, and $9.9&nbsp;million in 2016, 2015, and 2014, respectively.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR STYLE = "PAGE-BREAK-INSIDE:AVOID">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(3)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Loans on
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-accrual
</FONT>
	are included in the computation of average balances. Interest income on these loans is also included in loan income.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<A NAME="eolPage28"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D317189D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Table 2
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<U>
	RATE-VOLUME ANALYSIS
</U>
</B>
<B>
<I>
<U>
	(in thousands)
</U>
</I>
</B>
<B>
<U>
</U>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	This analysis attributes changes in net interest income either to changes in average balances or to changes in average interest rates for
	earning assets and interest-bearing liabilities. The change in net interest income that is due to both volume and interest rate has been allocated to volume and interest rate in proportion to the relationship of the absolute dollar amount of the
	change in each. All interest rates are presented on a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	tax-equivalent
</FONT>
	basis and give effect to tax-exempt interest income net of the disallowance of interest expense for federal income tax purposes, related to
	certain
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	tax-free
</FONT>
	assets. The loan average balances and rates include nonaccrual loans.
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Table 3
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<U>
	ANALYSIS OF NET INTEREST MARGIN
</U>
</B>
<B>
<I>
<U>
	(in thousands)
</U>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company experienced an increase in net interest income of $83.3&nbsp;million, or 20.2&nbsp;percent, for
	the year-ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, compared to 2015. This follows an increase of $62.0&nbsp;million, or 17.7&nbsp;percent, for the year-ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, compared to 2014. As noted above, the impact of the Marquette acquisition is
	included in these results. Average earning assets increased by $1.8&nbsp;billion, or 10.7&nbsp;percent, compared to the same period in 2015. Net interest margin, on a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	tax-equivalent
</FONT>
	basis, increased to
	2.88&nbsp;percent for 2016 compared to 2.64&nbsp;percent in 2015. As illustrated in Table 2, the 2016 and 2015 increases are primarily due to the favorable volume variances in earning assets.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company funds a significant portion of its balance sheet with noninterest-bearing demand deposits. Noninterest-bearing demand deposits
	represented 40.2&nbsp;percent, 41.8&nbsp;percent and 41.4&nbsp;percent of total outstanding deposits at December&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015 and 2014, respectively. As illustrated in Table 3, the impact from these interest-free funds was nine basis points
	in 2016, compared to eight basis points in 2015 and six basis points in 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company has experienced an
	increase in net interest income during the 2016 due to a volume variance of $63.0&nbsp;million and a rate variance of $20.2&nbsp;million. The Marquette acquisition also influenced these variances as 2016 was the first full year of Marquette&#146;s
	earning assets being included in the Company&#146;s Consolidated Balance Sheets. The average rate on earning assets during 2016 has increased by 28 basis points, while the average rate on interest-bearing liabilities increased by five basis points,
	resulting in a 23 basis point increase in spread. The volume of loans has increased from an average of $8.4&nbsp;billion in 2015 to an average of $10.0&nbsp;billion in 2016. Loan-related earning assets tend to generate a higher spread than those
	earned in the Company&#146;s investment portfolio. By design, the Company&#146;s investment portfolio is moderate in duration and liquid in its composition of assets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During 2017, approximately $1.1&nbsp;billion of available for sale securities are expected to have principal repayments.&nbsp;This includes
	approximately $386&nbsp;million which will have principal repayments during the first quarter of 2017.&nbsp;The available for sale investment portfolio had an average life of 54.3 months, 44.8 months, and 43.6 months as of December&nbsp;31, 2016,
	2015, and 2014, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Provision and Allowance for Loan Losses
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The allowance for loan losses (ALL) represents management&#146;s judgment of the losses inherent in the Company&#146;s loan portfolio as of the
	balance sheet date. An analysis is performed quarterly to determine the appropriate balance of the ALL. The analysis reflects loan quality trends, including the levels of and trends related to
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-accrual
</FONT>
	loans, past due loans, potential problem loans, criticized loans and net charge-offs or recoveries, among other factors. After the balance sheet analysis is performed for the ALL, the provision for loan losses is computed as the amount required to
	adjust the ALL to the appropriate level.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	29
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage30"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>

<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D317189D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Table 4 presents the components of the allowance by loan portfolio segment. The Company manages
	the ALL against the risk in the entire loan portfolio and therefore, the allocation of the ALL to a particular loan segment may change in the future. Management of the Company believes the present ALL is adequate considering the Company&#146;s loss
	experience, delinquency trends and current economic conditions. Future economic conditions and borrowers&#146; ability to meet their obligations, however, are uncertainties which could affect the Company&#146;s ALL and/or need to change its current
	level of provision. For more information on loan portfolio segments and ALL methodology refer to Note 3, &#147;Loans and Allowance for Loan Losses,&#148; in the Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Table 5 presents a five-year summary of the Company&#146;s ALL. Also, please see &#147;Quantitative and
	Qualitative Disclosures About Market Risk&#151;Credit Risk Management&#148; on page 56 in this report for information relating to nonaccrual, past due, restructured loans, and other credit risk matters. For more information on loan portfolio
	segments and ALL methodology refer to Note 3, &#147;Loans and Allowance for Loan Losses,&#148; in the Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As illustrated in Table 5 below, the ALL increased as a percentage of total loans to 0.87&nbsp;percent as of December&nbsp;31, 2016, compared
	to 0.86&nbsp;percent as of December&nbsp;31, 2015. Based on the factors above, provision for loan loss totaled $32.5&nbsp;million for the year-ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, which is an increase of $17.0&nbsp;million, or 109.7&nbsp;percent, compared
	to the same period in 2015. This provision for loan losses totaled $15.5&nbsp;million and $17.0&nbsp;million for the years-ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	30
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Noninterest Income
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	A key objective of the Company is the growth of noninterest income to provide a diverse source of revenue not directly tied to interest
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	rates.&nbsp;Fee-based
</FONT>
	services are typically
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-credit
</FONT>
	related and are not generally affected by fluctuations in interest rates. Noninterest income increased in 2016 by
	$9.6&nbsp;million, or 2.1&nbsp;percent, compared to 2015 and decreased in 2015 by $32.2&nbsp;million, or 6.5&nbsp;percent, compared to 2014. The increase in 2016 is primarily attributable to higher unrealized equity gains on alternative investments,
	increases in bank-owned and company-owned life insurance income, and brokerage income, offset by lower trust and securities processing income. The decrease in 2015, compared to 2014, is primarily attributable to lower trust and securities processing
	income and unrealized equity losses on alternative investments, which was partially offset by an increase in gains on securities available for sale.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company&#146;s
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	fee-based
</FONT>
	services offer multiple products and services to customers which
	management believes will more closely align to the customer&#146;s product demand with the Company. The Company is currently emphasizing
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	fee-based
</FONT>
	services including trust and securities processing, bankcard,
	securities trading/brokerage and cash/treasury management. Management believes that it can offer these products and services both efficiently and profitably, as most have common platforms and support structures.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	31
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Noninterest income and the year-over-year changes in noninterest income are summarized in Table 6 above. The
	dollar change and percent change columns highlight the respective net increase or decrease in the categories of noninterest income in 2016 compared to 2015, and in 2015 compared to 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Trust and securities processing income consists of fees earned on personal and corporate trust accounts, custody of securities services, trust
	investments and investment management services, and mutual fund assets servicing. This income category decreased by $22.2&nbsp;million, or 8.5&nbsp;percent in 2016, compared to 2015, and decreased by $26.0&nbsp;million, or 9.0&nbsp;percent in 2015,
	compared to 2014. The Company increased fee income from institutional and personal investment management services by $1.8&nbsp;million in 2016, compared to 2015, and $5.3&nbsp;million in 2015, compared to 2014.&nbsp;Increases of $1.4&nbsp;million
	and $2.4&nbsp;million were attributable to Marquette in 2016 and 2015, respectively. Fund administration and custody services fee income decreased by $2.8&nbsp;million in 2016, compared to 2015, and increased by $2.9&nbsp;million in 2015, compared
	to 2014.&nbsp;Advisory fee income from the Scout funds decreased $22.9&nbsp;million to $33.1&nbsp;million in 2016 compared to 2015 and decreased $35.6&nbsp;million in 2015 compared to 2014 due to changes in the underlying assets under management.
	During the period of December&nbsp;31, 2015 to December&nbsp;31, 2016 total Scout AUM increased from $27.2&nbsp;billion to $27.3&nbsp;billion, while during the period of December&nbsp;31, 2014 to December&nbsp;31, 2015 Scout AUM decreased from
	$31.2&nbsp;billion to $27.2&nbsp;billion. Additionally, the mix of AUM has shifted between the two periods from 78.5&nbsp;percent fixed income and 21.5&nbsp;percent equity as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 to 82.8&nbsp;percent fixed income and
	17.2&nbsp;percent equity as of December&nbsp;31, 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Brokerage fees increased $6.1&nbsp;million, or 51.7&nbsp;percent, in 2016 compared
	to 2015 primarily due to an increase in
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	12b-1
</FONT>
	income driven by an increase in interest rates.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Gains on sales of securities available for sale decreased $1.9&nbsp;million in 2016 compared to 2015 and increased by $6.3&nbsp;million in
	2015 compared to 2014. The Company&#146;s goal in the management of its
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	available-for-sale
</FONT>
</FONT>
	securities portfolio is to maximize return within the Company&#146;s
	parameters of liquidity goals, interest rate risk and credit risk. This can result in differences from period to period in the amount of realized gains.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Equity earnings on alternative investments increased $14.9&nbsp;million to an unrealized gain position in 2016 compared to a loss position in
	2015 and decreased $16.2&nbsp;million in 2015 compared to 2014, primarily due to changes in the valuation of the underlying PCM fund investments.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	32
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Noninterest Expense
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Noninterest expense increased in 2016 by $28.2&nbsp;million, or 4.0&nbsp;percent, compared to 2015 and increased in 2015 by $38.1&nbsp;million,
	or 5.7&nbsp;percent, compared to 2014. The main drivers of this increase from 2015 to 2016 were salaries and employee benefits expense, other noninterest expense, and equipment expense. The main drivers of this increase from 2014 to 2015 were
	salaries and employee benefits expense, equipment expense, and legal and professional expense. Table 7 below summarizes the components of noninterest expense and the respective year-over-year changes for each category.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Salaries and employee benefits expense increased $26.3&nbsp;million, or 6.5&nbsp;percent, in 2016 and
	$47.9&nbsp;million, or 13.4&nbsp;percent, in 2015. The increase in both 2016 and 2015 is primarily due to higher employee base salaries, higher commissions and bonuses, and higher cost of benefits. The Marquette acquisition contributed
	$8.2&nbsp;million of increased salary and employee benefits expense in 2016 since it was the first full year of salary and benefits expense after the Marquette acquisition. From 2015 to 2016, base salaries increased by $9.1&nbsp;million, or
	3.6&nbsp;percent, commissions and bonuses increased by $11.4&nbsp;million, or 12.8&nbsp;percent, and employee benefits increased by $5.8&nbsp;million, or 9.1&nbsp;percent. Included within commission and bonuses expense in 2016 and 2015 is
	acquisition related severance expense of $0.9&nbsp;million and $2.4&nbsp;million, respectively,
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	non-acquisition
</FONT>
	related expense of $4.2&nbsp;million and $4.6&nbsp;million, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Equipment expense increased $3.7&nbsp;million, or 5.9&nbsp;percent and $9.9&nbsp;million, or 18.5&nbsp;percent in 2016 and 2015, respectively.
	This increase is driven by increased computer hardware and software expenses for investments for regulatory requirements, cyber security and the ongoing modernization of our core systems in both years.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Legal and consulting expense decreased $5.1&nbsp;million, or 19.5&nbsp;percent, in 2016 and increased $6.0&nbsp;million, or 29.3&nbsp;percent
	in 2015. This decrease in 2016 and increase in 2015 were driven by $4.8&nbsp;million in legal and consulting expense related expense related to the Marquette acquisition recognized in 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Processing fees expense decreased $6.1&nbsp;million, or 11.9&nbsp;percent, and $4.7&nbsp;million, or 8.4&nbsp;percent in 2016 and 2015,
	respectively. This reduction is primarily driven by decreased fees paid by the advisor to distributors of the Scout Funds.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	33
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage34"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D317189D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	A contingency reserve of $20.3&nbsp;million was recognized in the Company&#146;s Consolidated
	Statements of Income in 2014 due to a settlement agreement entered into on June&nbsp;30, 2014, to resolve objections to its calculation of the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	earn-out
</FONT>
	amount owed to the sellers of PCM and a related incentive
	bonus calculation for the employees of PCM. Fair value adjustments subsequent to the settlement date were included in Other noninterest expense.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Other noninterest expense increased $6.5&nbsp;million, or 25.6&nbsp;percent and decreased $4.4&nbsp;million, or 14.9&nbsp;percent, in 2016 and
	2015, respectively. The increase in 2016 was primarily driven by an increase of $3.1&nbsp;million in fair value adjustments to the contingent consideration liabilities on acquisitions and $2.7&nbsp;million of expense related to the
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	buy-out
</FONT>
	and termination of certain marketing and referral agreements in the Company&#146;s institutional investment management business. The decrease in 2015 was primarily driven by fair value adjustments to the
	contingent consideration liabilities on acquisitions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Total acquisition related expenses recognized in noninterest expense during 2016
	totaled $5.0&nbsp;million, and in 2015 totaled $9.8&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Income Taxes
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Income tax expense totaled $48.2&nbsp;million, $43.2&nbsp;million and $45.4&nbsp;million in 2016, 2015 and 2014, respectively.&nbsp;These
	amounts equate to effective rates of 23.3&nbsp;percent, 27.1&nbsp;percent and 27.3 percent&nbsp;for 2016, 2015 and 2014, respectively.&nbsp;The decrease from 2015 to 2016 is primarily attributable to an increase in federal tax credits and a larger
	portion of income earned from excludable life insurance policy gains. The decrease in the effective tax rate from 2014 to 2015 results from changes in the portion of income earned from
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	tax-exempt
</FONT>
	municipal
	securities. Due to the early adoption of ASU
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	No.&nbsp;2016-09,
</FONT>
	all excess tax benefits related to share-based awards were recognized in income tax expense for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For further information on income taxes refer to Note 16, &#147;Income Taxes,&#148; in the Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Business Segments
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company has
	strategically aligned its operations into the following three reportable segments (collectively, the Business Segments):&nbsp;Bank, Institutional Investment Management, and Asset Servicing.&nbsp;Senior executive officers regularly evaluate business
	segment financial results produced by the Company&#146;s internal reporting system in deciding how to allocate resources and assess performance for individual Business Segments.&nbsp;Previously, the Company had the following four Business
	Segments:&nbsp;Bank, Institutional Investment Management, Asset Servicing, and Payment Solutions.&nbsp;In the first quarter of 2016, the Company merged the Payments Solutions segment into the Bank segment to better reflect how the core businesses,
	products and services are being evaluated by management currently.&nbsp;The Company&#146;s Payment Solutions leadership structure and financial performance assessments are now included in the Bank segment, and accordingly, the reportable segments
	were realigned to reflect these changes. The management accounting system assigns balance sheet and income statement items to each Business Segment using methodologies that are refined on an ongoing basis.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	34
</P>

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Bank net income increased by $56.2&nbsp;million, or 65.0&nbsp;percent, to $142.8&nbsp;million for the year
	ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, compared to the same period in 2015. Net interest income increased $77.8&nbsp;million, or 19.1&nbsp;percent, for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, compared to the same period in 2015, primarily driven by strong
	loan growth, a change in the Company&#146;s earning asset mix, higher loan yields, and the acquisition of Marquette. As of the Acquisition Date, Marquette added earning assets with an acquired value of $1.2&nbsp;billion primarily from loan balances
	with an acquired value of $980.4&nbsp;million. Provision for loan losses increased by $17.0&nbsp;million to adjust the related ALL to the appropriate level based on the inherent risk in the loan portfolio for this segment.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Noninterest income increased $31.4&nbsp;million, or 11.2&nbsp;percent, over the same period in 2015 primarily driven by the following
	increases: unrealized gains on PCM equity method investments of $14.9&nbsp;million, brokerage and mutual fund income of $6.1&nbsp;million driven by an increase in
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	12b-1
</FONT>
	fees, bank-owned and company-owned life
	insurance income of $4.1&nbsp;million, healthcare deposit service charges of $3.5&nbsp;million, trust and securities processing income of $2.8&nbsp;million, insurance and annuities income of $1.7&nbsp;million, and miscellaneous noninterest income of
	$1.6&nbsp;million due to increased gains on the sale of other assets in the current year. These increases were partially offset by decreases of $1.9&nbsp;million in gains on securities available for sale and $1.0&nbsp;million in commercial and
	consumer deposit service charges.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Noninterest expense increased $25.2&nbsp;million, or 4.6&nbsp;percent, to $577.7&nbsp;million for the
	year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, compared to the same period in 2015. This increase was primarily driven by increases of $19.7&nbsp;million in salaries and benefits, $1.7&nbsp;million in regulatory fees, $1.6&nbsp;million in software and equipment
	expense, $1.6&nbsp;million in services and supplies, and $1.0&nbsp;million in amortization of intangibles. The increase in salaries and benefits is driven by increases of $11.3&nbsp;million in salary and wage expense, $6.8&nbsp;million of which is
	related to the acquisition of Marquette, $5.4&nbsp;million in bonus and commission expense, of which Marquette represented a decrease of $0.4&nbsp;million, and $3.0&nbsp;million in employee benefit expense, of which $1.8&nbsp;million is related to
	Marquette. The increase in employee benefit expense was driven, in part, by a $1.6&nbsp;million increase in the fair value of the Company&#146;s deferred compensation plan. Additionally, there was an increase in other noninterest expense of
	$2.9&nbsp;million, largely due to an increase of $2.5&nbsp;million in fair value adjustments to contingent consideration liabilities incurred in 2015, each being partially offset by a decline in operational losses in the comparative periods. These
	increases were partially offset by a decrease of $1.8&nbsp;million in legal and professional fees expense due to decreased acquisition costs related to Marquette in 2016 as compared to the prior period.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	35
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, Institutional Investment Management net income decreased
	$15.5&nbsp;million, or 90.7&nbsp;percent, compared to the same period in 2015. Noninterest income decreased $19.2&nbsp;million, or 20.2&nbsp;percent, due to a $22.2&nbsp;million decrease in advisory fees from the Scout Funds which was partially
	offset by an increase of $0.6&nbsp;million in advisory fees from separately managed accounts, both of which are driven by changes in AUM. During the period of December&nbsp;31, 2015 to December&nbsp;31, 2016 total Scout AUM increased from
	$27.2&nbsp;billion to $27.3&nbsp;billion, while during the period of December&nbsp;31, 2014 to December&nbsp;31, 2015 Scout AUM decreased from $31.2&nbsp;billion to $27.2&nbsp;billion. Additionally, the mix of AUM has shifted between the two periods
	from 78.5&nbsp;percent fixed income and 21.5&nbsp;percent equity as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 to 82.8&nbsp;percent fixed income and 17.2&nbsp;percent equity as of December&nbsp;31, 2016. The increase in noninterest expense of $1.9&nbsp;million, or
	2.7&nbsp;percent, as compared to the prior year was primarily driven by an increase of $7.3&nbsp;million in salaries and benefits expense driven by severance and increased incentives and increases in the fair value of the deferred compensation plan.
	Additionally, other noninterest expense increased $3.3&nbsp;million in 2016 due to a $2.7&nbsp;million
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	buy-out
</FONT>
	and termination of certain marketing and referral agreements and $0.6&nbsp;million in fair value
	adjustments to contingent consideration liabilities incurred in 2015. These increases were offset by decreases of $6.0&nbsp;million in fees paid by the advisor to third-party distributors of the Scout Funds, $1.3&nbsp;million in technology, service
	and overhead expenses as compared to the prior year, and $0.8&nbsp;million in marketing and business development expense. Noninterest expense included $4.5&nbsp;million and $5.8&nbsp;million of services and overhead allocations in 2016 and 2015,
	respectively.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, Asset Servicing net income increased $2.0&nbsp;million, or
	16.1&nbsp;percent, to $14.4&nbsp;million as compared to the same period in 2015. Net interest income increased $5.4&nbsp;million compared to the same period last year due to an increase in deposits coupled with an overall increase in deposit funds
	transfer
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	36
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage37"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D317189D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	credit. Noninterest income decreased $2.5&nbsp;million, or 2.8&nbsp;percent, largely due to decreased fund administration, fund transfer agency, and custody fees. As of December&nbsp;31, 2016,
	assets under administration totaled $188.7&nbsp;billion compared to $185.6&nbsp;billion at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and $198.3&nbsp;billion at December&nbsp;31, 2014. For the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, noninterest expense increased
	$1.0&nbsp;million, or 1.3&nbsp;percent, as compared to the same period last year, primarily due to an increase of $2.2&nbsp;million in salary and benefits expense, which was partially offset by decreases of $0.3&nbsp;million in marketing and
	business development expense, $0.3&nbsp;million in processing fees, and $0.3&nbsp;million in legal and professional fees expense.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Balance Sheet
	Analysis
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Loans and Loans Held For Sale
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Loans
	represent the Company&#146;s largest source of interest income. Loan balances held for investment increased by $1.1&nbsp;billion, or 11.8&nbsp;percent, in 2016. This increase was primarily driven by an increase of $503.2&nbsp;million, or
	18.9&nbsp;percent, in commercial real estate loans, $325.2&nbsp;million, or 78.1 percent, in construction real estate loans, and $205.1&nbsp;million, or 4.9&nbsp;percent, in commercial loans.
</P>

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Included in Table 11 is a five-year breakdown of loans by type. Business-related loans continue to represent
	the largest segment of the Company&#146;s loan portfolio, comprising approximately 84.1&nbsp;percent and 82.3&nbsp;percent of total loans and loans held for sale at the end of 2016 and 2015, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Commercial loans represent the largest percent of total loans. Commercial loans at December&nbsp;31, 2016 have increased $205.1&nbsp;million,
	or 4.9&nbsp;percent, as compared to December&nbsp;31, 2015, to 41.8&nbsp;percent of total loans. Commercial loans represented 44.6&nbsp;percent of total loans at December&nbsp;31, 2015. Despite the Company increasing its capacity to lend through
	increased commitments during 2016, commercial line utilization has remained low.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As a percentage of total loans, commercial real estate
	and construction real estate loans now comprise 37.1&nbsp;percent of total loans compared to 32.7&nbsp;percent in 2015. Commercial real estate increased $503.2&nbsp;million, or 18.9&nbsp;percent, and construction real estate loans increased
	$325.2&nbsp;million, or 78.1 percent, compared to 2015. Generally, these loans are made for working capital or expansion purposes and are primarily secured by real estate with a maximum
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	loan-to-value
</FONT>
</FONT>
	of 80&nbsp;percent. Most of these properties are owner-occupied and/or have other collateral or guarantees as security.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Asset based loans totaled $225.9&nbsp;million and represented 2.1&nbsp;percent of total loans as of December&nbsp;31, 2016. Factoring loans
	totaled $139.9&nbsp;million and represented 1.3&nbsp;percent of total loans as of December&nbsp;31, 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Residential real estate
	increased $56.1&nbsp;million, or 11.4&nbsp;percent, and represented 5.2&nbsp;percent of total loans. HELOC loans decreased $18.2&nbsp;million, or 2.5&nbsp;percent, and represent 6.8&nbsp;percent of total loans.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Nonaccrual, past due and restructured loans are discussed under &#147;Quantitative and Qualitative Disclosure about Market Risk &#150; Credit
	Risk Management&#148; in Item 7A on page 56 of this report.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Investment Securities
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company&#146;s investment portfolio contains trading,
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	available-for-sale
</FONT>
</FONT>
	(AFS), and
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	held-to-maturity
</FONT>
</FONT>
	(HTM) securities as well as FRB stock,
	Federal Home Loan Bank (FHLB) stock, and other miscellaneous investments. Investment securities totaled $7.7&nbsp;billion as of December&nbsp;31, 2016 and $7.6&nbsp;billion as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and comprised 40.1&nbsp;percent and
	43.0&nbsp;percent of the Company&#146;s earning assets, respectively, as of those dates.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	38
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage39"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D317189D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company&#146;s AFS securities portfolio comprised 84.1&nbsp;percent of the Company&#146;s
	investment securities portfolio at December&nbsp;31, 2016, compared to 89.9&nbsp;percent at
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	year-end
</FONT>
	2015. The Company&#146;s AFS securities portfolio provides liquidity as a result of the composition and
	average life of the underlying securities. This liquidity can be used to fund loan growth or to offset the outflow of traditional funding sources. The average life of the AFS securities portfolio increased from 44.8 months at December&nbsp;31, 2015
	to 54.3 months at December&nbsp;31, 2016 due to portfolio mix changes, a strategic decision to invest in longer-term securities, and rising interest rates driving down prepayment speeds on mortgage-backed securities. In addition to providing a
	potential source of liquidity, the AFS securities portfolio can be used as a tool to manage interest rate sensitivity. The Company&#146;s goal in the management of its AFS securities portfolio is to maximize return within the Company&#146;s
	parameters of liquidity goals, interest rate risk and credit risk.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Management expects collateral pledging requirements for public funds,
	loan demand, and deposit funding to be the primary factors impacting changes in the level of AFS securities. There were $5.7&nbsp;billion of AFS securities pledged to secure U.S. Government deposits, other public deposits, certain trust deposits,
	derivative transactions, and repurchase agreements at December&nbsp;31, 2016. Of this amount, securities with a market value of $1.8&nbsp;billion at December&nbsp;31, 2016 were pledged at the Federal Reserve Discount Window but were unencumbered as
	of that date.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Company&#146;s HTM securities portfolio consists of private placement bonds, which are issued primarily to refinance
	existing revenue bonds in the healthcare and education sectors. The HTM portfolio totaled $1.1&nbsp;billion as of December&nbsp;31, 2016, an increase of $448.8&nbsp;million, or 67.3&nbsp;percent, from December&nbsp;31, 2015. The average life of the
	HTM portfolio was 89 months at December&nbsp;31, 2016, compared to 81 months at December&nbsp;31, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The securities portfolio
	generates the Company&#146;s second largest component of interest income. The AFS and HTM securities portfolios achieved an average yield on a
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	tax-equivalent
</FONT>
	basis of 2.1&nbsp;percent for 2016, compared to
	2.0&nbsp;percent in 2015, and 1.9&nbsp;percent in 2014. Securities available for sale had a net unrealized loss of $92.2&nbsp;million at
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	year-end,
</FONT>
	compared to a net unrealized loss of $5.9&nbsp;million the
	preceding year. This market value change primarily reflects the impact of mid and longer-term market interest rate increases as of December&nbsp;31, 2016, compared to December&nbsp;31, 2015. These amounts are reflected, on an
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	after-tax
</FONT>
	basis, in the Company&#146;s Accumulated other comprehensive income (loss) in shareholders&#146; equity, as an unrealized loss of $57.5&nbsp;million at
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	year-end
</FONT>
	2016, compared to an unrealized loss of $3.7&nbsp;million for 2015.The
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<FONT STYLE="WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
	available-for-sale
</FONT>
</FONT>
	securities portfolio contains securities that have unrealized losses and are
	not deemed to be other-than-temporarily impaired (see the table of these securities in Note 4, &#147;Securities,&#148; in the Notes to the Consolidated Financial Statements on page 84 of this document). The unrealized losses in the Company&#146;s
	investments in direct obligations of U.S. Treasury obligations, U.S. government agencies, federal agency mortgage-backed securities, municipal securities, and corporates were caused by changes in interest rates. The Company does not have the intent
	to sell these securities and does not believe it is more likely than not that the Company will be required to sell these securities before a recovery of fair value. The Company expects to recover its cost basis in the securities and does not
	consider these investments to be other-than-temporarily impaired at December&nbsp;31, 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	39
</P>
